# UI Components

Use shadcn/ui for anything shadcn already provides. Do not build custom
buttons, cards, inputs, dialogs, tables, etc. when a shadcn primitive covers
the need — install/use the shadcn component and wire up the implementation
around it instead.

Keep shadcn's default padding, spacing, and sizing. Do not override a
component's built-in structural classes (height, padding, gap, radius) unless
there's a concrete reason tied to this project's design system.

Colors are the one dimension expected to change — theme tokens (background,
foreground, primary, status colors, etc.) can be customized freely to match
this project's palette.

When editing a shadcn component's className, always merge with `cn(...)`
rather than replacing the base classes — never break the base
`buttonVariants`/similar variant classes a component ships with.

This is a strong default, not an absolute lock: if there's a good reason to
deviate (accessibility, a real UX problem, a case shadcn doesn't cover), it's
fine to suggest it — just flag that it's a deviation from stock shadcn rather
than silently reskinning components.
